"use strict";(globalThis.webpackChunkportfolio=globalThis.webpackChunkportfolio||[]).push([[8130],{7735(e){e.exports=JSON.parse('{"archive":{"blogPosts":[{"id":"gabi-hartmann","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/gabi-hartmann","source":"@site/blog/2026-03-14-gabi-hartmann.md","title":"Gabi Hartmann","description":"Eclectic, polyglot jazz.","date":"2026-03-14T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"jazz","permalink":"/blog/tags/jazz"},{"inline":true,"label":"ottawa","permalink":"/blog/tags/ottawa"},{"inline":true,"label":"music","permalink":"/blog/tags/music"},{"inline":true,"label":"nac","permalink":"/blog/tags/nac"}],"readingTime":1.9,"hasTruncateMarker":false,"authors":[],"frontMatter":{"title":"Gabi Hartmann","description":"Eclectic, polyglot jazz.","slug":"gabi-hartmann","tags":["jazz","ottawa","music","nac"],"image":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dopnll2lm/image/upload/v1773508909/20260313_201253-2_reorma.jpg","hide_table_of_contents":false},"unlisted":false,"nextItem":{"title":"Stanley\'s Farm","permalink":"/blog/stanleys-farm"}},"content":"There was nothing inauspicious on Friday the 13th as [Gabi Hartmann](https://www.gabihartmannmusic.com/) took the [Fourth Stage](https://nac-cna.ca/en/venue/fourth-stage) at the [National Arts Centre](https://nac-cna.ca/en/) (NAC) to present her eclectic, ear-candied brand of jazz. With her, a jazz trio at the top of their game: [Florian Robin](https://www.instagram.com/florian_robin_kunz/) (piano), [J\xe9r\xf4me Arrighi](https://www.orchestrevictorhugo.fr/artistes/jerome-arrighi/) (bass), and [Arthur Alard](https://www.manusound.net/pages/bio.php?lang=de&mus=_bio/alard_a/) (drums).\\r\\n\\r\\n<figure style={{textAlign: \'center\'}}>\\r\\n  <img src=\\"https://res.cloudinary.com/dopnll2lm/image/upload/v1773531288/20260313_201253_icadkq.jpg\\" style={{width: \'70%\'}} />\\r\\n  <figcaption style={{fontSize: \'0.8em\'}}>Hartmann and the trio.</figcaption>\\r\\n</figure>\\r\\n\\r\\nFor me, Hartmann\'s music is like a **mango sorbet**. It\'s like the tropical and the continental coming together to make something that\'s sweet, smooth, and everyone can enjoy.\\r\\n\\r\\nMuch of her work is inspired by rhythms from Brazil, the Caribbean, and West Africa. A lot of gospel, too. The arrangements are sophisticated, but always accessible. Always voice- and melody-first. And her singing is so silky, even when it occasionally ventures into melisma territory.\\r\\n\\r\\nThe whole show was great, but I had two favourite moments. One was Robin\'s piano solo in \\"[Fall Down](https://youtu.be/3MFZF0PJLoI?si=ksr1-WMsuPRDmq2q),\\" which was full of pointed emotion. He was amazing throughout, as were Arrighi and Alard, but that solo was something else. The other moment was when Hartmann had the audience sing the main lick of \\"[Drink the Ocean](https://youtu.be/Fi16ELXh1XM?si=7Y2O2nq-UvRkqy0m)\\" as a wordless refrain, over and over.\\r\\n\\r\\nI recommend Hartmann\'s music without reservations, both the recordings and seeing it live with the jazz trio, which are quite different experiences.\\r\\n\\r\\n<figure style={{textAlign: \'center\'}}>\\r\\n  <img src=\\"https://res.cloudinary.com/dopnll2lm/image/upload/v1773456618/20260313_213106_cjg268.jpg\\" style={{width: \'70%\'}} />\\r\\n  <figcaption style={{fontSize: \'0.8em\'}}>Hartmann sat on stage with the trio to sing her fourth and final encore.</figcaption>\\r\\n</figure>\\r\\n\\r\\nLastly, a word about the venue. The Fourth Stage is a small venue at the NAC with all the trappings of a jazz club: atmospheric lighting, unassigned table seating, bar and drinks. The large street-facing windows also add to the ambiance as the bustle of the city bleeds into the venue. \\r\\n\\r\\nOn a snowy night like last night, it was a cool vibe."},{"id":"stanleys-farm","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/stanleys-farm","source":"@site/blog/2026-03-08-stanleys.md","title":"Stanley\'s Farm","description":"A visit to a sugar bush in late winter.","date":"2026-03-08T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"sugar bush","permalink":"/blog/tags/sugar-bush"},{"inline":true,"label":"ottawa","permalink":"/blog/tags/ottawa"},{"inline":true,"label":"outing","permalink":"/blog/tags/outing"}],"readingTime":1.76,"hasTruncateMarker":false,"authors":[],"frontMatter":{"title":"Stanley\'s Farm","description":"A visit to a sugar bush in late winter.","slug":"stanleys-farm","tags":["sugar bush","ottawa","outing"],"image":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dopnll2lm/image/upload/v1773007912/20260307_130123_nmfwec.jpg","hide_table_of_contents":false},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Gabi Hartmann","permalink":"/blog/gabi-hartmann"},"nextItem":{"title":"Rock, paper, scissors","permalink":"/blog/rock-paper-scissors"}},"content":"This weekend, I visited [Stanley\'s Olde Maple Lane Farm](https://stanleysfarm.com/) with my family. The farm\'s located in Edwards, a rural community south of Ottawa, which I\'d never been to before. It was 8\xb0C and rainy, but we had a good time.\\r\\n\\r\\nStanley\'s main attraction is their sugar bush, which visitors can go through on a tractor ride. The ride was lovely and took a good 15 minutes. It went around much of the farm, not just through the sugar bush, and took us by the fields where the animals were. We saw horses, cows, donkeys, and sheep.\\r\\n\\r\\n<figure style={{textAlign: \'center\'}}>\\r\\n  <img src=\\"https://res.cloudinary.com/dopnll2lm/image/upload/v1773007912/20260307_131748_cot1rx.jpg\\" style={{width: \'70%\'}} />\\r\\n  <figcaption style={{fontSize: \'0.8em\'}}>Detail from a mural at the farm. Love the art style.</figcaption>\\r\\n</figure>\\r\\n\\r\\nWe also saw animals at the barn. There was a two-day-old calf suckling nonstop. The calf\'s tail was up, which we were told was a sign of happiness. And there was a very pregnant ewe lying down in her stall. We could see the lamb(s) kicking inside her. She looked exhausted, but was still a few weeks away from lambing.\\r\\n\\r\\nThere were walking paths through the sugar bush, but we didn\'t take them. We were a little pressed for time and did not dress appropriately for trudging through the mud and melting snow. We were also a little let down that we couldn\'t collect sap from the tapped trees like they let guests do at [The Log Farm](https://thelogfarm.com/).\\r\\n\\r\\n<figure style={{textAlign: \'center\'}}>\\r\\n  <img src=\\"https://res.cloudinary.com/dopnll2lm/image/upload/v1773007912/20260307_130123_nmfwec.jpg\\" style={{width: \'70%\'}} />\\r\\n  <figcaption style={{fontSize: \'0.8em\'}}>Sap vapour rising in the sugar shack.</figcaption>\\r\\n</figure>\\r\\n\\r\\nBut the highlight of the visit was the historical sugar shack. It\'s a structure from the early 20th century that they keep running to entertain guests. The gentleman tending the fire told us it was the first boil of the year. The sweet vapour of evaporating sap permeated the air in and around the shack. It was very special, like being inside a cloud of maple syrup."},{"id":"rock-paper-scissors","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/rock-paper-scissors","source":"@site/blog/2026-03-02-rock-paper-scissors.md","title":"Rock, paper, scissors","description":"Kindness always wins.","date":"2026-03-02T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"work","permalink":"/blog/tags/work"},{"inline":true,"label":"kindness","permalink":"/blog/tags/kindness"},{"inline":true,"label":"musings","permalink":"/blog/tags/musings"}],"readingTime":1.49,"hasTruncateMarker":false,"authors":[],"frontMatter":{"title":"Rock, paper, scissors","description":"Kindness always wins.","slug":"rock-paper-scissors","tags":["work","kindness","musings"],"image":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dopnll2lm/image/upload/v1772463747/20260302_095326_ocva94.jpg","hide_table_of_contents":false},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Stanley\'s Farm","permalink":"/blog/stanleys-farm"},"nextItem":{"title":"Primeval Well","permalink":"/blog/primeval-well"}},"content":"Lately, I\'ve been under pressure at work. Some of this pressure is caused by people who themselves are under pressure and take out their frustration on me.\\r\\n\\r\\nI believe this sort of trickle-down unkindness is a universal thing. Everyone who works experiences this at some point. I\'m sorry if this sounds jaded.\\r\\n\\r\\nBut personally, I refuse to perpetuate the cycle. I do my darnedest to keep my cool. Don\'t get defensive. Don\'t blame others. Focus on solutions and use words that uplift rather than tear down.\\r\\n\\r\\nI always ask myself, \\"If someone leaked the transcript of this interaction, would my conduct be irreproachable? Would my loved ones feel proud of how I reacted?\\"\\r\\n\\r\\n<figure style={{textAlign: \'center\'}}>\\r\\n  <img src=\\"https://res.cloudinary.com/dopnll2lm/image/upload/v1772463747/20260302_095326_ocva94.jpg\\" style={{width: \'70%\'}} />\\r\\n  <figcaption style={{fontSize: \'0.8em\'}}>I like how the light hits my curtains.</figcaption>\\r\\n</figure>\\r\\n\\r\\nI\'m pushing forty. Technically middle-aged. I\'m not na\xefve. I know anger is a powerful motivator. Anger can bring about change, even necessary change, like nothing else can. Maybe this is what the people who are angry with me think, that by being angry with me, they can spur me to become more competent.\\r\\n\\r\\nBut I don\'t feel that way. I think anger is best directed at _systems_, not _individuals_. I\'ve never solved\u2014_really_ solved\u2014issues with people through anger. Quite the contrary. Some of my deepest regrets come from times when I failed to control my temper.\\r\\n\\r\\nHere\'s what I believe. Remember when we were kids and we\'d play rock, paper, scissors, but add a random fourth element that always beat everything? I think mine was the t-rex. That\'s what kindness is to me. Yes, anger is useful, it can get stuff done, but it can\'t beat kindness. \\r\\n\\r\\nKindness always wins."},{"id":"primeval-well","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/primeval-well","source":"@site/blog/2026-02-22-primeval-well.md","title":"Primeval Well","description":"Black metal and bluegrass go great together.","date":"2026-02-22T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"primeval well","permalink":"/blog/tags/primeval-well"},{"inline":true,"label":"avant-garde bar","permalink":"/blog/tags/avant-garde-bar"},{"inline":true,"label":"black metal","permalink":"/blog/tags/black-metal"},{"inline":true,"label":"bluegrass","permalink":"/blog/tags/bluegrass"},{"inline":true,"label":"ottawa","permalink":"/blog/tags/ottawa"},{"inline":true,"label":"music","permalink":"/blog/tags/music"}],"readingTime":1.43,"hasTruncateMarker":false,"authors":[],"frontMatter":{"title":"Primeval Well","description":"Black metal and bluegrass go great together.","slug":"primeval-well","tags":["primeval well","avant-garde bar","black metal","bluegrass","ottawa","music"],"image":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dopnll2lm/image/upload/v1771817386/igor-profile-2026_z9eyev.png","hide_table_of_contents":false},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Rock, paper, scissors","permalink":"/blog/rock-paper-scissors"}},"content":"[Primeval Well](https://primevalwell.bandcamp.com/) headlined an intimate show at the [Avant-Garde Bar](https://avantgardebar.myshopify.com/) this past Saturday, February 21, 2026.\\r\\n\\r\\n<figure style={{textAlign: \'center\'}}>\\r\\n  <img src=\\"https://res.cloudinary.com/dopnll2lm/image/upload/v1771816992/20260221_202713_gwhayt.jpg\\" style={{width: \'70%\'}} />\\r\\n  <figcaption style={{fontSize: \'0.8em\'}}>My bathroom selfie at the Avant-Garde.</figcaption>\\r\\n</figure>\\r\\n\\r\\nThe show opened with [Gr\xf3a Willing](https://www.lastingtale.ca/), a local act that plays a sort of minimal, acoustic-only black metal. It was nice. Trance-like. They did four songs, which were all a little samey, but I liked it for what it was.\\r\\n\\r\\nNext up were [Nirthal](https://www.facebook.com/Nirthal), also local and billed as \\"King Diamond worship.\\" I didn\'t care much for their stuff, but others in the audience enjoyed it.\\r\\n\\r\\nPrimeval Well played last. They were **great**. They played selections from their second LP, [*Talkin\' in Tongues with Mountain Spirits*](https://primevalwell.bandcamp.com/album/talkin-in-tongues-with-mountain-spirits) (2021). My favourite tracks were \\"She Flies Undead\\" and \\"Where All Things are Forgotten.\\"\\r\\n\\r\\n<figure style={{textAlign: \'center\'}}>\\r\\n  <img src=\\"https://res.cloudinary.com/dopnll2lm/image/upload/v1771819212/capital-noise/copy_of_20260221_224014_yhjmqw_ce734e.jpg\\" style={{width: \'70%\'}} />\\r\\n  <figcaption style={{fontSize: \'0.8em\'}}>Primeval Well</figcaption>\\r\\n</figure>\\r\\n\\r\\nPrimeval Well\'s shtick is mixing black metal and bluegrass, which sounds like a really strange pairing, but they make it work. They engage with Appalachian folk spirituality so earnestly, it elevates their brand of atmospheric black metal. Full marks from me.\\r\\n\\r\\nA special mention about [Ryan Clackner](https://daily.bandcamp.com/features/ryan-clackner-feature), the band\'s guitarist, vocalist, and main creative force. You get a pretty good idea how inventive and well developed his playing is from the albums, but seeing it live is something else. And a great singer to boot. What a beast."}]}}')}}]);